      • getNearestFunctionName

        public static String getNearestFunctionName(Node n)
        Gets the function's name. This method recognizes the forms:
        • &#123;'name': function() ...&#125;
        • &#123;name: function() ...&#125;
        • function name() ...
        • var name = function() ...
        • var obj = {name() {} ...}
        • qualified.name = function() ...
        • var name2 = function name1() ...
        • qualified.name2 = function name1() ...
        Parameters:
        n - a node whose type is Token.FUNCTION
        Returns:
        the function's name, or null if it has no name

      • isLValue

        public static boolean isLValue(Node n)
        Determines whether this node is used as an L-value. Notice that sometimes names are used as both L-values and R-values.

        We treat "var x;" as a pseudo-L-value, which kind of makes sense if you treat it as "assignment to 'undefined' at the top of the scope". But if we're honest with ourselves, it doesn't make sense, and we only do this because it makes sense to treat this as syntactically similar to "var x = 0;".

        Parameters:
        n - The node
        Returns:
        True if n is an L-value.
